h3. Summary
It has been observed on across some instances that when enabling Dutch language language support  for a service desk project that if prompted to confirm the email templates section they may not save the translations as confirmed.

This happens if ANY customization has been made to the project before adding a language and changing the default project language.

h3. Environment
See internal comments for examples of environments where the bug has been reproduced and where it has not

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Created service desk project
# Enable Dutch language support
# If prompted confirm and save the email template translations
# Refresh the page after saving

h3. Expected Results
The yellow notification will go away and the confirmations will be saved. Thus the default project language can be changed. 

h3. Actual Results
On some instances after refreshing the email templates are highlighted as needing confirmation still. As such the default project language can not be changed as confirmations are still required. 
 
h3. Notes
Looking at the REST calls being made we are getting the below response which seem to show all is updated as expected:

h4. Rest Endpoint
/rest/analytics/1.0/publish/bulk

h5. Request - POST
{code:json}
[
	{
		"name":"servicedesk.admin.settings.languagesupport.managetranslation.translation.confirmed",
		"properties":{
			"sdVersion":"3.3.0-OD",
			"projectId":10021,
			"sessionId":"ca3c2d1e-7fc6-bfa3-471d-42d81230c3ac"
			
		},
		"timeDelta":-1366
		
	},

	{
		"name":"servicedesk.admin.settings.languagesupport.managetranslation.confirm.notification.content",
		"properties":{
			"sdVersion":"3.3.0-OD",
			"projectId":10021,
			"sessionId":"ca3c2d1e-7fc6-bfa3-471d-42d81230c3ac"
			
		},"timeDelta":-1366
		
	}
]
{code}

h5. Response
{code}
200 OK
{code}

h4. Rest Endpoint
/rest/servicedesk/lingo-integration/1/manage-translations/{project_key}

h5. Request - POST
{code:json}
{
	"providerKey":"com.atlassian.servicedesk.servicedesk-notifications-plugin:sd-customer-notifications-template-translations-provider",
	"languageTag":"nl-NL",
	"fieldUpdates":
		[
			{
				"content":"${issue.key} ${issue.summary}",
				"changeType":"unchanged",
				"logicalId":"sd.notifications.custom.email.subject"
				
			},
			{
				"content":"{html_temnplate_here}",
				"changeType":"confirmed",
				"logicalId":"sd.notifications.custom.email.html.template"
				
			},
			{
				"content":"{css_template_here}",
				"changeType":"confirmed",
				"logicalId":"sd.notifications.custom.email.template.css"
				
			},
			{
				"content":"{plain_text_template_here}",
				"changeType":"unchanged",
				"logicalId":"sd.notifications.custom.email.plaintext.template"
			}
		],
	"panelTitle":"Email templates"
}
{code}

h5. Response 
{code} 204 EMPTY {code}

h4. Other Notes
*There are also no errors in the Splunk logs*

Interestingly if you add a newline to the end of the HTML template this will save, however I have not been able to find a similar method for the CSS template, which still prevents the default language from being changed for the project.

h3. Workaround
The only confirmed way to get around to this I have found is to:
# Create a new service desk project.
# Add the language.
# Confirm any translation changes required and save.
# Change the default project language.
# Continue with customization options.

h3. Summary

When a user sets the language as Spanish and vendor calls on:

{noformat}
/rest/servicedeskapi/request/{issueKey}/approval
{noformat}

it returns an English version of the {{name}} and {{finalDecision}}:

{code}
{
    "size": 1,
    "start": 0,
    "limit": 50,
    "isLastPage": true,
    "_links": {
        "self": "https://annecalantog.atlassian.net/rest/servicedeskapi/request/ISD-3/approval",
        "base": "https://annecalantog.atlassian.net",
        "context": ""
    },
    "values": [
        {
            "id": "1",
            "name": "Waiting for approval",
            "finalDecision": "pending",
            "canAnswerApproval": true,
            "approvers": [
                {
                    "approver": {
                        ...
                    },
                    "approverDecision": "pending"
                }
            ],
            "createdDate": {
                "iso8601": "2018-11-16T04:50:44+0000",
                "jira": "2018-11-16T12:50:44.040+0800",
                "friendly": "Hoy 4:50 AM",
                "epochMillis": 1542343844040
            },
            "_links": {
                "self": "https://<instance-name>.atlassian.net/rest/servicedeskapi/request/10045/approval/1"
            }
        }
    ]
}
{code}

Expected Output: Should be in Spanish as well

h3. Investigation

As per [Translating resolutions, priorities, statuses, and issue types|https://confluence.atlassian.com/adminjiracloud/translating-resolutions-priorities-statuses-and-issue-types-788726079.html], the status can be customized. REST API {{/rest/api/2/issue/<issueIdOrKey>}} respects this and returns proper translation of the status, but {{/rest/servicedeskapi/request/<issueKey>/approval}} does not. 

However, when renaming the status/transition in Jira Settings -> Workflows , then it reflects the changes for the {{name}} of the status/transition, which boils down to what the hierarchy of the requirement is, to use name provided in the workflow vs the custom translation
